WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.120
Alright, let's talk about the handoff.

2
00:00:02.500 --> 00:00:06.320
This is Stage 4 in the pipeline, and it is
make or break.

3
00:00:06.680 --> 00:00:07.820
You've done discovery.

4
00:00:08.140 --> 00:00:10.760
You know the story. The seller is qualified.

5
00:00:11.180 --> 00:00:14.040
They're motivated. And they're ready to hear
an offer.

6
00:00:14.560 --> 00:00:17.820
Now it's time to hand this lead to the
acquisition team.

7
00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:21.740
And I cannot stress enough how much a good
handoff matters.

8
00:00:22.100 --> 00:00:24.580
Bad handoffs kill deals that should have
closed.

9
00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:27.540
Here's what the process looks like.

10
00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:29.980
First, complete your CRM notes.

11
00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:31.900
Every field filled out.

12
00:00:32.080 --> 00:00:34.340
Every detail from discovery documented.

13
00:00:34.800 --> 00:00:39.260
The acquisition manager should be able to
read your notes and understand the seller's

14
00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:43.420
full situation without having to call you
and ask 20 questions.

15
00:00:43.640 --> 00:00:47.220
If they have to chase you down for basic
info, that's on you.

16
00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:51.420
Second, brief the acquisition manager.

17
00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:55.040
And I don't mean just drop a lead in their
queue and walk away.

18
00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:57.000
Give them real context.

19
00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:59.780
Something like, this is Diane in Dayton.

20
00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:05.300
She's had a duplex for 11 years, and she's
completely burned out from tenant issues.

21
00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:10.420
She's two months behind on taxes and wants
to sell before the end of summer.

22
00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:15.140
She inherited the place from her father, and
there's some emotional attachment there.

23
00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:16.920
So be sensitive to that.

24
00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:19.500
See how much information is packed into
that?

25
00:01:19.640 --> 00:01:23.420
The acquisition manager can walk into that
call completely prepared.

26
00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:26.580
They know the story. They know the pressure
points.

27
00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:28.340
And they know where to be careful.

28
00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:34.640
Third, either warm transfer the seller directly
to the acquisition manager while you've

29
00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:37.800
still got them on the phone or set a
specific appointment.

30
00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:42.480
You might say something like, what I'd like
to do next is connect you with our

31
00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:47.180
acquisitions team. They're the ones who will
evaluate the property and put together a

32
00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:51.420
formal offer for you. Can I set up a call
for tomorrow at 2 p.m.?

33
00:01:51.420 --> 00:01:53.220
Give them a specific time.

34
00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:54.600
Don't leave it vague.

35
00:01:55.660 --> 00:02:00.020
And fourth, frame the handoff for the seller
so they know what's coming.

36
00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:01.920
Don't just disappear on them.

37
00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:05.200
Say something like, so here's what happens
next.

38
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:08.280
Our acquisition manager is going to reach
out to you.

39
00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:12.600
They'll ask a few more detailed questions
about the property, and then they'll put

40
00:02:12.600 --> 00:02:13.880
together an offer for you.

41
00:02:14.160 --> 00:02:16.180
No pressure, no obligation.

42
00:02:16.280 --> 00:02:18.860
You can take as long as you need to think
about it.

43
00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:22.640
That gives the seller confidence that
there's a real process here.

44
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:24.400
Real people are involved.

45
00:02:24.620 --> 00:02:27.700
They're not being bounced around randomly
between strangers.

46
00:02:28.640 --> 00:02:33.820
Before you move any lead to stage four, make
sure you've got the full seller story

47
00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:39.580
documented, their motivation clearly articulated,
their timeline confirmed, the property

48
00:02:39.580 --> 00:02:45.560
condition described, their price expectations
noted, the decision maker confirmed, their

49
00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:50.820
financial situation understood, including
mortgage balance and any liens or back taxes,

50
00:02:51.260 --> 00:02:56.820
their best contact time and method noted,
any hot buttons or sensitivities flagged, and

51
00:02:56.820 --> 00:02:57.680
the acquisition manager.

52
00:02:57.700 --> 00:03:01.580
If you can check all of those, you've done
your job.

53
00:03:01.860 --> 00:03:07.520
A thorough handoff is what separates someone
who's just okay at this from someone who's

54
00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:08.480
genuinely good.

55
00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:13.480
Let me tell you what kills handoffs, because
I've seen all of these happen.

56
00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:15.160
Incomplete information.

57
00:03:15.700 --> 00:03:20.460
The acquisition manager has to re-ask
everything you already covered, and the seller

58
00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:21.420
gets frustrated.

59
00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:24.340
I already told the other person all of this.

60
00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:27.580
That's a terrible start to what should be a
smooth process.

61
00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:30.440
Next, no context on motivation.

62
00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:35.640
The acquisition manager doesn't know the
emotional drivers, accidentally steps on a

63
00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.460
landmine, and the seller shuts down
completely.

64
00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:40.280
And no warm introduction.

65
00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:45.180
The seller gets a random call from someone
new and their guard goes right back up.

66
00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:48.000
They're thinking, Oh, great, here we go
again.

67
00:03:48.520 --> 00:03:51.160
Avoid those three things and you're going to
be in great shape.

68
00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:54.540
That's discovery and handoff.

69
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.460
Now let's go practice.

70
00:03:56.980 --> 00:04:01.500
Your roleplay for this module is a tired
landlord who's been dealing with a duplex for

71
00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:03.760
11 years and has just about had it.

72
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:04.840
Show us what you've got.
